The极限of panic
Copenhagen – We often hear that the world as we know it will end in a description of ecological collapse.
In fact, the basic idea has been with us since the Rome Club's seminal work "The Limits to Growth" was released over forty years ago.
But time is not forgiving.
The 1972 Limits to Growth warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
But thereafter, we saw financial panics without any genuine shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, the resources created by human genius are more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
But the basic premise of The Limits to Growth still holds: we are caught up in a trend, distracted by misleading solutions to minor issues, while ignoring the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism gave way, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book, _Silent Spring_, sparked both a panic about pollution and the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title _The Population Bomb_ said it all.
At the first Earth Day in 1970, people were pessimistic.
The intent of " Limits to Growth" was to make people concerned about resource depletion.
This is our fate because too many people consume too much.
Even if our genius buys us some time, we will ultimately destroy the Earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is for stagnating economic growth itself, reducing consumption, recycling, and forcing people to have fewer children to achieve social stability at significantly poorer levels than now.
This view still resonates today, despite being thoroughly mistaken.
For example, the authors of _Limits to Growth_ predicted that by 2013 the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
However, while commodity prices have rebounded somewhat recently, they overall have fallen to about one-third of the level from 150 years ago.
Technological innovations have replaced mercury in batteries, dental amalgams, and thermometers, leading to a 98% decrease in mercury consumption and a 90% drop in prices by the year 2000.
More broadly, since 1946, supplies of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc have exceeded demand thanks to discoveries of new reserves and more economical new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were expected to have been depleted in 1990 and 1992, respectively; now, reserves of both exceed the 1970 levels despite our much-greater consumption.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled America's potential natural gas resources and halved their price.
Regarding economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries seeing an increase of 24 times.
The Limits to Growth went wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource of all: our own ingenuity.
The population growth slowed down since the 1960s.
Food supplies have not collapsed (there are 1.5 billion hectares of arable land in use, with an additional 27 billion hectares in reserve).
The prevalence of malnutrition has been halved, dropping from 35% to 16% of the world's population.
Pollution has not troubled us either.
The Club of Rome imagines a pastoral past where we had no air pollution from particulates and were all happy farmers, and a future where chimney stacks from heating will make us unable to breathe. Reality is the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, and yet nearly 3 million people died from air pollution each year –相当于每500人中就有一人– with most of these deaths due to indoor air pollution.
Now, this ratio has fallen to one death for every 2,000 people.
Despite the number of deaths from pollution still being higher than those from malaria, the mortality rate is declining rather than rising.
Despite this, the ideas fostered by The Limits of Growth continue to shape the thinking of both the public and elites.
Let recycling be an example: it is typically just a feel-good姿态 that is costly in terms of its environmental impact and ineffective in its results.
For example, paper typically comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The programs and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, while they protect resources that are not actually threatened.
Similarly, concerns about overpopulation have led to self-destructive policies such as China’s one-child policy and forced sterilizations in India.
Moreover, while pesticides and other pollutants are blamed for killing half of humanity, good pesticide regulation ensures that only about 20 deaths occur annually in the United States, while the use of pesticides creates a supply of cheaper and more abundant food.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture – the movement spurred by fears of pesticides – would impose an additional annual cost of $100 billion on the United States.
Agricultural efficiency will decline by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland would be required — an area equivalent to half the size of modern diamond-rich California.
Rising prices will lead to a decrease in fruit and vegetable consumption, resulting in serious negative health impacts (including an annual increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths).
Being fixated on dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on the genuine global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, claiming 15 million lives each year – a quarter of all deaths – while easily treatable diseases still claim that many lives.
The solution lies in economic growth.
When people are lifted out of poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of poor people by nearly one billion.
This has led to significant improvements in hygiene, lifespan, and quality of life.
The four-decade history since the publication of "Limits to Growth" shows that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring in more than $100 trillion annually by the end of the century, the benefits of which vastly outweigh those of timid “feel-good” policies fueled by fear-mongering.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our infinite potential to create a brighter future.
